[Generation of valuable information and the problem of goal self-setting in 
living systems].

[Article in Russian]

Chernavskiĭ DS(1), Chernavskaia NM.

Author information:
(1)Lebedev Physical Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences, Research Computing 
Center, Lomonosov Moscow State University, Moscow, Russia.

The problem of origination of capacity for goal self-setting is discussed. It 
was shown that the definition "goal" in living systems differs from the 
definition "target function" in physical problems concerned with nonliving 
systems. It was also shown that the main goal of the elements of a system is the 
storage of information. In biology, this goal is the extension of the principle 
of struggle for existence. Conditions were determined that the dynamic system 
describing the goal self-setting process must satisfy. It was shown that living 
systems meet these conditions. In inorganic nature, such systems may also arise 
but only as a result of long-term evolution, after which they become living.

